My understanding, and I've followed the development of the Intel family since=
=20
the 8080, each generation since the 386 has introduced better and faster=20
instructions. I.E.:
The 486 introduced I.E.E.E floating point instructions by incorporating an=20
FPU on board. The first few generations were flaky, so Intel disabled the=20
dodgy ones and sold then as 486SX, I.E. without the FPU. Later generations=20
were better, this is why you only find slow 486SX's ;-) Therefore 486's, with=
=20
working FPU's can calculate floats faster than 386's, but you must generate=20
the proper codes to take advantage of this.The Pentium's improved the FPU log=
ic and introduced pipelining. The first=20
generations of Pentiums had faulty FPu logic programmed into them, the=20
Pentium Bug, but subsequent ones were fine. These added instructions are=20
faster again then the 486 equivulents. Also, the pipelining needs careful=20
instruction ordering to take full advantage of it's speed improvements,=20
again, something the compiler must know about to utilise to full effect.=20
According the the PGCC site GCC does this poorly, but that info seems to be=20
dated, GCC3.1.x might be better. This is one of the areas I am researching=20
closely to get an answer.MMX added the ability to perform matrix calculations=
 on int's with single=20
instructions and using special DMA features within the Pentium to speed this =

up. Two problems with this:
1) int's are not very useful for most matrix calculations, floats would be=20
betters.
2) this is not something that can be optimised well by a compiler. It need to=
=20
be identified and provided for in the sources.
I.E. not much use to anyone, but makes great ad copy ;-)The PentiumPro improv=
ed the pipeline enormously. Again, a properly written=20
compiler should be able to optimise for this, once it can organise the code=20
properly.The PIII added MMX-type instructions for floats! Now this IS useful!=
=20
Graphic-Intensive programs can take greate advantage of this, but it must be =

provided for in the source code. Compilers can not, usually optimise for this=
=20
sort of thing. XFree86 and DRI are two prime examples that do provide for=20
this, so the PIII can run XFree86 and DRI quite a bit faster, IF it's=20
compiled for these SSE instructions!Not sure what improvements the P4 introdu=
ce? I think it's mostly just speed=20
improvements rather than any execution changes.So, The difference between the=
 386 and the PentiumMMX 'should' yield a=20
significant speed boost if optimised correctly. There are faster floating=20
point instructions and pipelining that need optimising for. I'm not sure if=20
GCC can optimise properly for the pipelining, at least the PGCC group found=20
significant improvements to add to GCC2.95.3 to gain speed improvements of=20
upto 30%. 30% of 48 hours is 14.4 hours. Of course none of this will have any=
=20
effect on O/I bound processes but GUI's are mostly CPU bound. I am also=20
finding out about object pre-linking optimisations which should give even=20
better performance for QT and KDE.Now if I had another PIII for my box, I cou=
ld take advantage of those SSE=20
instructions to optimise XFree86 as well!> kevinAn, of course, I've loads of =
